  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Bank Secrecy Act\n- Strong emphasis on financial institution reporting\n- Aggressive prosecution with significant criminal penalties\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified anti-money laundering directives\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Centralized regulatory framework\n- Focus on transparency and international cooperation\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Sophisticated regulatory framework\n- Strict asset disclosure requirements\n- Advanced financial intelligence capabilities\n- Strong emphasis on international collaboration\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historical banking secrecy traditions\n- Increasing transparency in recent years\n- Complex compliance requirements\n- Sophisticated financial monitoring systems\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict capital controls\n- Increasing international compliance standards\n- Heavy penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Singapore\n- Stringent regulatory environment\n- Advanced technological monitoring\n- Strong international cooperation\n- Significant penalties for violations\n\nKey comparative considerations:\n- Regulatory intensity\n- Technological monitoring capabilities\n- International cooperation mechanisms\n- Criminal and civil penalty structures\n- Financial institution reporting requirements\n\nThis overview represents general comparative perspectives, acknowledging variations in specific implementation.",
